[0.334119, "o", "\u001b[1G\u001b[0K⠙"]
[0.348499, "o", "\u001b[1G"]
[0.348815, "o", "\u001b[0K"]
[2.743995, "o", "\u001b[1m\r\n  AQUEDUCT — an LLM buys specific data from a big Tap (via the aqueduct skill)\r\n\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[2.744367, "o", "  \u001b[2mdataset:\u001b[0m NASA exoplanet archive (real)   \u001b[2mquestion:\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[1mWhat is the closest exoplanet to Earth discovered by the Transit method with a temperate equilibrium temperature (between 250 and 320 K)? Give the 3 nearest, with name, distance (pc), temperature, and host star.\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[36m  0  WITHOUT AQUEDUCT — the agent answers from memory alone (no data)\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[2m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[20.745363, "o", "  \u001b[2mThe three nearest transiting exoplanets with equilibrium temperatures in 250–320 K are likely: (1) **Gliese 12 b** — ~12.2 pc, ~315 K, host star Gliese 12 (M dwarf); (2) **TRAPPIST-1 d** — ~12.4 pc, ~288 K, host TRAPPIST-1; and (3) **TRAPPIST-1 e** — ~12.4 pc, ~251 K, host TRAPPIST-1. Confidence is moderate: the rankings depend on assumed albedo for the temperature estimates, and a closer or newer transiting candidate may exist that I am not recalling precisely.\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[20.944616, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[36m  1  SERVE — compile the exoplanet archive into a Tap and run it\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[2m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[21.619749, "o", "  \u001b[32m✓\u001b[0m server wallet \u001b[2m(pre-funded)\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[21.655388, "o", "  \u001b[32m✓\u001b[0m \u001b[1m1,529 planets\u001b[0m live on http://localhost:8700  \u001b[2m(0.0001 pathUSD/row)\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[21.655678, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[36m  2  DISCOVER — the agent reads the Tap's terms for free (skill: --schema)\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[2m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[24.391438, "o", "  \u001b[2mcolumns:\u001b[0m name:string  host_star:string  discovery_year:integer  method:string  distance_pc:number  period_days:number  radius_earth:number  mass_earth:number  eq_temp_k:integer\r\n\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[36m  3  PLAN — the LLM translates the question into a paid query\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[2m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[31.762217, "o", "  \u001b[2mLLM query →\u001b[0m \u001b[36m{\"select\":[\"name\",\"distance_pc\",\"eq_temp_k\",\"host_star\"],\"filters\":[{\"field\":\"method\",\"op\":\"eq\",\"value\":\"Transit\"},{\"field\":\"eq_temp_k\",\"op\":\"gte\",\"value\":250},{\"field\":\"eq_temp_k\",\"op\":\"lte\",\"value\":320}],\"sort\":[{\"field\":\"distance_pc\",\"dir\":\"asc\"}],\"limit\":3}\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[36m  4  BUY — the agent pays per row over an MPP session (skill: paid query)\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[2m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[31.923473, "o", "  \u001b[32m✓\u001b[0m agent wallet \u001b[2m(pre-funded)\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[38.249035, "o", "  \u001b[32m✓\u001b[0m bought \u001b[1m3 rows\u001b[0m for \u001b[1m0.0003 pathUSD\u001b[0m  \u001b[2msettled 0xa6d6a1356151a73d…\u001b[0m\r\n      \u001b[2mhttps://explore.testnet.tempo.xyz/tx/0xa6d6a1356151a73d8e639b1781fea56f9b5c5f803faa72c064d37e0ad9b4595c\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[36m  5  ANSWER — the LLM answers from only the rows it bought\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[2m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[52.94556, "o", "  The closest temperate (250–320 K) transiting exoplanet in this set is **TOI-4336 A b**, with the three nearest as follows:\r\n\r\n1. **TOI-4336 A b** — 22.55 pc, 309 K, host star TOI-4336 A\r\n2. **TOI-2134 c** — 22.62 pc, 306 K, host star TOI-2134\r\n3. **LP 890-9 c** — 32.43 pc, 272 K, host star LP 890-9\r\n\r\nNotable points:\r\n- The top two are nearly equidistant (22.55 vs. 22.62 pc — a difference of about 0.07 pc) and both sit near the warm end of the temperate range (~306–309 K), comparable to a hot terrestrial environment.\r\n- **LP 890-9 c** is the most interesting astrobiologically: at 272 K its equilibrium temperature is close to Earth's (~255 K), placing it well within the temperate band. Its host, LP 890-9, is a cool M dwarf, and this planet is a known member of a system considered among the more promising nearby habitable-zone candidates—though it lies roughly 10 pc farther out than the other two.\r\n\r\nAll three were found by the transit method, so radius (not mass) is the directly measured quantity; equilibrium temperatures assume modeled albedo and provide no direct constraint on actual surface conditions or atmospheres.\r\n\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[36m  6  THE DIFFERENCE\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[2m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[2mwithout Aqueduct:\u001b[0m a guess from training memory — plausible, unverifiable, stale\r\n"]
[52.945656, "o", "  \u001b[2mwith Aqueduct:\u001b[0m    3 exact rows from the live archive, 0.0003 pathUSD, settled on-chain — verifiable + current\r\n"]
[52.945918, "o", "\u001b[32m\u001b[1m\r\n  ✓ DONE — answered from 3 paid rows, never touching the other 1,526.\r\n\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[52.983505, "o", "\u001b[1G\u001b[0K⠙"]
[52.986124, "o", "\u001b[1G\u001b[0K"]
